<section xml:id="section-introduction-to-exponent-rules">

    <title>Introduction to Exponent Rules</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-apply-exponent-rules" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>In this section, we're going to look at some rules or properties we use when simplifying expressions that involve multiplication and exponents.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtubelist="PLmuZCPhWPt-dj61wWyTluBykvvQE1pWnB"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Exponent Basics</title>

        <p>Before we discuss any exponent rules, we need to quickly remind ourselves of some important concepts and vocabulary.</p><!-- that are discussed in greater detail in the appendix <xref ref="appendix-arithmetic" text="title"/>.</p>-->

        <p>When working with expressions with exponents, we have the following vocabulary: <me>\text{base}^{\text{exponent}} = \text{power}</me> For example, when we calculate <m>8^{2} = 64</m>, the <term>base</term><idx><h>exponent</h><h>base</h></idx><idx><h>base</h></idx> is <m>8</m>, the <term>exponent</term><idx><h>exponent</h></idx> is <m>2</m>, and the expression <m>8^{2}</m> is called the 2nd <term>power</term><idx><h>exponent</h><h>power</h></idx><idx><h>power</h></idx> of 8. </p>

        <p>The other foundational concept is that if an exponent is a positive integer, the power can be rewritten as repeated multiplication of the base.  For example, the 4th power of <m>3</m> can be written as <m>4</m> factors of <m>3</m> like so: <me>3^{4} = 3 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 </me> </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Products and Exponents</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Product Rule</title>

            <p>If we write out <m>3^5\cdot 3^2</m> without using exponents, we'd have: <me>
            3^5 \cdot 3^2 = \left(3 \cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3\right) \cdot \left(3 \cdot 3\right)</me>If we then count how many <m>3</m>s are being multiplied together, we find we have <m>5+2=7</m>, a total of seven <m>3</m>s.<md>
                <mrow>3^5\cdot 3^2 \amp= 3^{5+2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 3^7</mrow>
                </md></p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>x^2\cdot x^3</m>.</p>
                <p>To simplify <m>x^2\cdot x^3</m>, we write this out in its expanded form, as a product of <m>x</m>'s, we have<md>
                    <mrow>x^2\cdot x^3 \amp=(x\cdot x)(x \cdot x \cdot x)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=x\cdot x\cdot x \cdot x \cdot x</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=x^5</mrow>
                </md>Note that we obtained the exponent of <m>5</m> by adding <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <p>This is our first rule, the <term>Product Rule</term><idx><h>exponent</h><h>product rule</h></idx>: when multiplying two expressions that have the same base, we can simplify the product by adding the exponents. <men xml:id="equation-product-rule">
            x^m \cdot x^n = x^{m+n}</men></p>

        <exercise>
            <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Exponents/exponentsMultiplication0.pg" />
        </exercise>


    <paragraphs>
        <title>Power to a Power Rule</title>

            <p>The second rule is an extension of the first rule.  If we write out <m>\left(3^5\right)^2</m> without using exponents, we'd have <m>3^5</m> multiplied by itself: <md>
                <mrow>\left(3^5\right)^2 \amp= \left(3^5\right)\cdot \left(3^5\right)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= \left(3\cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3 \cdot 3 \right) \cdot \left(3 \cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3\right) </mrow>
            </md>If we again count how many <m>3</m>s are being multiplied, we have a total of two groups each with five <m>3</m>s.  So we'd have <m>2\cdot 5=10</m> instances of a <m>3</m>.<md>
                <mrow>\left(3^5\right)^2 \amp= 3^{2\cdot 5}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 3^{10}</mrow>
                </md></p>
    </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\left(x^2\right)^3</m>.</p>
                <p>To simplify <m>\left(x^2\right)^3</m>, we write this out in its expanded form, as a product of <m>x</m>'s, we have<md>
                    <mrow>\left(x^2\right)^3 \amp=\left(x^2\right) \cdot \left(x^2\right)\cdot\left(x^2\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(x \cdot x)\cdot (x \cdot x)\cdot (x \cdot x)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=x^6</mrow>
                </md>Note that we obtained the exponent of <m>6</m> by multiplying <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

            <p>We have our second rule, the <term>Power to a Power Rule</term><idx><h>exponent</h><h>power to a power rule</h></idx>: when a base is raised to an exponent and that expression is raised to another exponent, we multiply the exponents. <me>\left(x^m\right)^n = x^{m \cdot n}</me></p>

        <exercise>
            <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/Exponents/exponentsMultiplication20.pg" />
        </exercise>


